'''Charles Debrille Poston''' (April 20, 1825&nbsp;– June 24, 1902) was an American [[explorer]], [[Prospecting|prospector]], author, politician, and [[Civil service|civil servant]].  He is referred to as the "Father of Arizona" due to his efforts lobbying for creation of the territory.  Poston was also [[Arizona Territory]]'s first Delegate to the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]].

==Background==

Poston was born near [[Elizabethtown, Kentucky]] to Temple and Judith Debrille Poston.  His father was a printer and he served as a [[printer's devil]].{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=17}}  Poston was orphaned at the age of twelve, and was [[Apprenticeship|apprenticed]] to the local [[county clerk]], Samuel Haycraft.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=17}}{{sfn|Sacks|1963|p=34}}  Following his apprenticeship, he moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] where he clerked for the [[Tennessee Supreme Court]] while [[reading law]].<ref name=ARobit>{{cite news|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84020558/1902-06-25/ed-1/seq-1/#words=POSTON&proxtext=poston|title=Col. C. D. Poston Died Suddenly|date=June 25, 1902|work=Arizona Republican|page=1}}</ref>  Poston married Haycraft's daughter, Margaret, in September 1848 and the couple had a daughter, Sarah Lee Poston, who reached adulthood.  Margaret Poston became paralyzed on February 12, 1851, possibly from a stroke while giving birth to a second child,  and was cared for by relatives until her death from cancer on February 26, 1884.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=17}}{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}  On July 27, 1885, Poston married former newspaper typesetter Martha "Mattie" Tucker.  The couple separated shortly afterwards, but there is no evidence they ever divorced.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=26}}

==Early exploration and mining efforts==

Poston traveled to [[California]] as part of the [[California Gold Rush|Gold Rush]] and took a clerk position at the [[San Francisco]] [[Customs House]] in February 1851.  Poston was demoted in 1853 and complained that his replacement was a professional gambler and political appointee.{{sfn|Sacks|1963|p=34}}  While at this 
job, he became involved with a group of French bankers interested in the lands of the recently negotiated [[Gadsden Purchase]].{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=18}}  In late 1853, with the bankers' backing, Poston joined with [[Mining engineering|mining engineer]] [[Herman Ehrenberg]] to organize an expedition into the territory Mexico was expected to sell to the United States.  Taking a ship from San Francisco, the two became shipwrecked near the [[Mexico|Mexican]] port of [[Guaymas]].  They were then detained temporarily by Mexican authorities as suspected [[Filibuster (military)|filibusters]] before heading north to the Gadsden territory.  The expedition visited [[San Xavier del Bac]] and [[Ajo, Arizona|Ajo]], collecting mineral samples along the way, before traveling down the [[Gila River]].{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=18}}{{sfn|Trimble|1977|p=213}}  At [[Fort Yuma]], a U.S. Army post near the confluence of the Gila and [[Colorado River]], Poston first met the fort's commander Major [[Samuel P. Heintzelman]].{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}  While at Fort Yuma Poston surveyed a townsite on the south side of the river a mile below the fort, at [[Jaeger's Ferry]].  Poston sold the townsite called [[Colorado City (Yuma County, Arizona)|Colorado City]] for $20,000 when he returned to San Francisco.{{sfn|Lingenfelter|1978|p=15}}

[[File:Fort Cerro in Arizona.jpg|250px|left|thumb|''The mining town and fort of Cerro Colorado, established by Poston and Major Heintzelmen.'']]
After returning to San Francisco, Poston left for the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] in search of [[Capital (economics)|capital]] to fund a mining operation in the newly acquired territory.  After several unsuccessful attempts, he was introduced to several [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] investors by Heintzelman.  On March 24, 1856, [[US$]]2&nbsp;million was secured to found the Sonora Exploring and Mining Company with Heintzelman as company president and Poston as managing supervisor.{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=19}}  The company set up headquarters in [[Tubac, Arizona]] and began mining operations in the nearby [[Santa Rita Mountains]] and elsewhere. Poston served as [[alcalde]] of the settlement and became known as "Colonel" Poston in the town of roughly 800 people.  Using the authority granted to him by the government of New Mexico Territory, he printed his own money and officiated over marriages, divorces, and the baptisms of children.{{sfn|Trimble|1977|p=215}}  This continued until Father Macheboeuf, the [[vicar]] of Bishop [[Jean-Baptiste Lamy]], was sent from [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]] to investigate the goings-on in Tubac. The validity of the marriages Poston had performed was questioned by the vicar, and a US$700 donation made before Father Macheboeuf sanctified the unions.{{sfn|Powell|1976|p=42}}  Charles Poston's brother, John, was murdered by Mexican outlaws at [[Cerro Colorado, Arizona|Cerro Colorado]] in southern Arizona, the town was established by Charles Poston.{{sfn|Sherman|Sherman|1969|p=23}}

Mining operations produced US $3000 per day in silver until 1861.  With the withdrawal of Union troops due to the [[American Civil War]], Tubac saw an increase in hostilities from local [[Apache]]s and the settlement had to be abandoned.{{sfn|Trimble|1977|p=216}}

==Arizona Territory==
[[File:John Poston's grave.jpg|right|thumb|300px|''John Poston's grave, the brother of Charles Poston who was murdered by Mexican outlaws at Cerro Colorado, Arizona in 1861.'']]
After being forced to leave Tubac due to the Apache [[Siege of Tubac|siege]], Poston went to [[Washington D.C.]] and worked for General Heintzelman as a civilian aide.  During this time Heintzelman introduced him to President [[Abraham Lincoln]].{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}  Poston in turn used this time to lobby both Lincoln and Congress for creation of an Arizona Territory, advertising the benefits of the area's mineral wealth to the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] cause.  Toward the end of the process Poston attended an oyster dinner where the [[Slate (elections)|slate]] of territorial positions was divided among [[Lame duck (politics)|lame duck]] congressmen and Poston was selected as an Indian Agent for the new territory.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=15}}

Poston commissioned [[Tiffany & Co.]] to create a US$1500 [[inkwell]] from Arizona silver 
and presented the inkwell to Lincoln upon signing of the [[Arizona Organic Act]].  On 12 March 1863 Poston was appointed superintendent of Indian affairs.{{sfn|Powell|1976|pp=43-4}}  This appointment was followed by his election as Delegate to the [[U.S. House of Representatives]] on 18 July 1864.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=21}}  During his term of service, Poston submitted bills aimed at settling private land claims and to establish [[Indian reservation]]s along the Colorado river.{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}  In 1865, Poston chose not to return to Arizona during his run for reelection, and was defeated by [[John Noble Goodwin]].{{sfn|Powell|1976|p=46}}  A final run for election to the territorial delegate position failed in 1866.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=24}}

==Writing==
After losing his position in Congress, Poston opened a law office in Washington D.C.
In 1867 he traveled to Europe, spending time in both [[London]] and [[Paris]].  He then returned to Washington and in 1868 published a travel book, ''Europe in the Summer-Time''.  This was followed by [[United States Secretary of State|U.S. Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] commissioning Poston to deliver the [[Burlingame Treaty]] to the [[Emperor of China]] and to study irrigation and immigration in Asia. After China, Poston continued to India where he developed a fascination with the [[Parsi people]] and [[Zoroastrianism]].  He reached Egypt by early 1869 and was in Paris by April of that year. After living a year in Paris he moved to London where he spent the next six years.  During this time he worked as an editor of a London newspaper, [[Foreign correspondent (journalism)|foreign correspondent]] to the ''New York Tribune'', and as a "counselor-at-law".{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=24}}  Poston also wrote several books during this time, publishing ''The Parsees'' in 1872, ''The Sun Worshippers of Asia'' in 1877, and his poem ''Apache Land'' in 1878.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=25}}
His work, ''Building a State in Apache Land'' was published in installments by ''Overland Monthly'' between July and October 1894.{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}

==Later life==
[[File:Older Charles D. Poston.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Poston in his later years]]
Poston returned to the United States in time for the [[Centennial Exposition]] in [[Philadelphia]].  Through his acquaintance with [[John Bigelow]], he then became a campaign worker for [[Samuel J. Tilden]] during the [[U.S. presidential election of 1876]].  Poston expected a [[Consul (representative)|consul]] position in London if Tilden had won the election, but instead was made register of the United States land office at [[Florence, Arizona]] from July 1877 till June 1879.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=25}}  During his time in Florence he became interested in building a Parsi [[fire temple]] on a nearby hill, paying for construction of a road to the summit.{{sfn|Goff|1985|pp=25-6}}  The temple itself was decorated with a blue and white flag depicting a red sun and built upon the ruins of an older Indian structure.<ref name="Stanley">{{cite news|url=http://www.azcentral.com/story/travel/local/history/2014/03/25/arizona-father-charles-poston/6870811/|title=Arizona Explained: Charles Poston was an eccentric|last=Stanley|first=John|date=March 25, 2014|work=Arizona Republic}}</ref>  Construction ended when Poston ran out of funds.<ref name="Barney">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=897&dat=19510719&id=_4xaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ElADAAAAIBAJ&pg=6562,1749128|title=Last Days of Charles Poston, State Pioneer|last=Barney|first=James M.|date=July 19, 1951|work=Prescott Evening Courier|page=6}}</ref>  He attempted to raise additional money, even writing to the [[Shah of Iran]], but his efforts failed and the temple's eternal flame failed shortly thereafter.<ref name="Stanley"/>  This unusual interest led to Poston being criticized as a crank and eccentric.{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}

Following his time in Florence he moved to [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]] and supported himself with a variety of positions including lecturer, mining and railroad promoter, and writer.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=26}}  In 1884 he became a consular agent in [[Nogales, Arizona|Nogales]] followed by an assignment as a civilian military agent in [[El Paso, Texas]] in 1887 and as employee of [[U.S. Geological Survey]] in 1889.{{sfn|Dillon|1999|pp=735-6}}{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=27}}

[[File:PostonButte-inscription.jpg|thumb|Inscription on the tomb of Charles D. Poston on Poston Butte in Florence, AZ.]]
Poston declined into obscurity until 1897 when [[Whitelaw Reid]] published an account detailing Poston's situation.  As a result, the Arizona Territorial legislature awarded Poston a pension of US$25/month in 1899 and increased this to US$35/month in 1901.{{sfn|Goff|1985|p=29}}  Poston died from apparent heart failure on June 24, 1902 in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix, Arizona Territory]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85066387/1902-06-25/ed-1/seq-9/#words=Poston&proxtext=poston|title=Father of Arizona Passes to the Beyond|date=June 25, 1902|work=The San Francisco Call|page=9}}</ref>

Despite his previously stated wish to be buried at the summit of [[Poston Butte|Primrose Hill]], Poston was initially buried in a [[pauper's grave]] in Phoenix.<ref name="Barney"/>  His remains were removed from Phoenix and moved to [[Florence, Arizona]], on the 100th anniversary of his birth, and buried on Primrose Hill, renamed, Poston Butte where he had never completed his "Temple to the Sun".  He was entombed in an official ceremony led by Governor [[George W. P. Hunt]].{{sfn|youtuber|1976|p=49}}

==Television depictions==

Poston was portrayed in the 1965 episode "A City Is Born" by later [[governor of California|Governor]] and [[U.S. President]] [[Ronald W. Reagan]] on the [[Television syndication|syndicated]] television series ''[[Death Valley Days]]''. In the story line, Poston is a mining developer and surveyor engaged in a race against time to reach [[San Diego, California|San Diego]], California, for an important meeting with bankers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0556535/?ref_=nm_flmg_act_01|title=A City Is Born|date=October 22, 1965|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=May 13, 2015}}</ref>

In another ''Death Valley Days'' segment in 1966, [[Robert Taylor (actor)|Robert Taylor]], Reagan's successor as the series host, played Poston in the episode "The Day All Marriages Were Cancelled". The story stemmed from a dispute between Poston and the [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] bishop, who questioned how Poston through his role as [[alcalde]] could perform secular marriages at no costs to the couples involved in the absence of available priests. During a civil trial, the church relents, and the marriages were declared legal once again. Willard Sage played the role of Father McCabe in this episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0556774/?ref_=tt_ep_pr|title="The Day All Marriages Were Cancelled" on ''Death Valley Days''|publisher=Internet Movie Data Base|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref>

